Data Description:¶

The dataset well use for this python project- well call it fake or real news. This dataset has a shape of 77964. The first column identifies the news, the second and third are the title and text, and the fourth column has labels denoting whether the news is REAL or FAKE. The dataset takes up 29.2MB This dataset is about fake and real news, most of the articles are political. It was provided by Hassan Amin and it was collected 2 years ago. It contains the title of the article in question , the article itself and the label: whether it is fake or real news.

Problem to be solved:¶

Fake news has become one of the biggest problems of our age. It has serious impact on our online as well as offline discourse. One can even go as far as saying that, to date, fake news poses a clear and present danger to western democracy and stability of the society. However, detecting fake news is no easy task. That's why we'll be building a model that detects fake news and we will aim to make it as accurate as possible.

Technical details:¶

Packages and libraries:¶

  • Pandas: Pandas is a great library for manipulating data and it is widely used for data analysis in python.
  • Matplotlib & Seaborn: Matplotlib is a great library for vizualizing data. Seaborn is basically what makes our vizualizations prettier and cooler and probably easier to understand.
  • SKLearn: Sci-kit Learn is a great machine learning library. You have access to many algorithms with just a couple of lines. It also provides the metrics used for evaluation.
  • Wordcloud: We used this library to vizualize a wordcloud and get a better understanding about the data.
  • Tensorflow: Tensorflow is a deep learning library. We used it to buil an RNN model since it is a powerful algorithm for NLP problems.
  • Pipline: We used this class (provided by sklearn) to combine tfidf and countvectorizer
  • countvectorizer & tfidf transformer: They are used for word vectorization in order to prepare text data for use in algorithms

# Splitting into train/test set
X = df['text']
y = df['label']
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.20, random_state=1)

Build Models¶

  • Naive Bayes: Naive Bayes is simple yet a powerful algorithm that relies on the bayes theorem to calculate probabilities and estimates the prediction.
  • Logistic Regression: Despite its name, logistic regression is classification algorithm. It is known for its great ability for binary classification. It uses a sigmoid activation function to calculate the probability and predict the label according to some threshhold.
  • Passive Agressive Classifier:Passive-Aggressive algorithms are generally used for large-scale learning. It is one of the few online-learning algorithms. In online machine learning algorithms, the input data comes in sequential order and the machine learning model is updated step-by-step.
  • Support Vector Machine:: linear svm is considered by many the best linear model. Using optimization algorithms, svm decides the best hyperplane that separates classes. It works well with high dimensional data.
  • RNN: rnn are known for their great ability with sequence data, such as text data. For this model, we used a 5-layer model: an embedding layer, 2 bidirectional (for better performance, it is better to calculate probability of a word considering past and future words) LSTM layers (to avoid vanishing gradients problem), a simple rnn layer and an output layer.

Prepare our Data : Tokenization and Vectorization¶

In the next step, we will classify the news texts as fake or true using classification algorithms. We will perform this classification using three algorithms one by one. First, we will obtain the term frequencies and count vectorizer that will be included as input attributes for the classification model and the target attribute that we have defined above will work as the output attribute. To bind the count vectorizer, TF-IDF and classification model together, the concept of the pipeline is used. A machine learning pipeline is used to help automate machine learning workflows. They operate by enabling a sequence of data to be transformed and correlated together in a model that can be tested and evaluated to achieve an outcome, whether positive or negative.

In [ ]:
#  Initialize a TfidfVectorizer
vectorizer = Pipeline([('vect', CountVectorizer()), ('tfidf', TfidfTransformer())])
#Fit and transform train set, transform test set
X_train_vectorized=vectorizer.fit_transform(X_train) 
X_test_vectorized=vectorizer.transform(X_test)
In [ ]:
# Preparing Data for RNN
max_vocab = 10000
tokenizer = Tokenizer(num_words=max_vocab)
tokenizer.fit_on_texts(X_train)
# tokenize the text into vectors 
X_train_rnn = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences(X_train)
X_test_rnn = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences(X_test)
X_train_rnn = tf.keras.preprocessing.sequence.pad_sequences(X_train_rnn, padding='post',maxlen =256)
X_test_rnn = tf.keras.preprocessing.sequence.pad_sequences(X_test_rnn, padding='post',maxlen=256)
y_train = np.asarray(y_train).astype(np.float32)
y_test = np.asarray(y_test).astype(np.float32)

  • rnn are known for its great ability with sequence data, such as text data. For this model, we used a 5-layer model: an embedding layer, 2 bidirectional (for better performance, it is better to calculate probability of a word considering past and future words) LSTM layers (to avoid vanishing gradients problem), a simple rnn layer and an output layer.
In [ ]:
# RNN classifier
model = tf.keras.Sequential([
    tf.keras.layers.Embedding(max_vocab, 50),
    tf.keras.layers.Bidirectional(tf.keras.layers.LSTM(64,activity_regularizer=l1(0.001),  return_sequences=True)),
    tf.keras.layers.Bidirectional(tf.keras.layers.LSTM(16)),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(64, activation='tanh'),
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.8),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(1)
]) 

model.summary()

early_stop = tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=2, restore_best_weights=True)
model.compile(loss=tf.keras.losses.BinaryCrossentropy(from_logits=True),
              optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(1e-4),
              metrics=['accuracy'])

history = model.fit(X_train_rnn, y_train, epochs=10,validation_split=0.1, batch_size=30, shuffle=True, callbacks=[early_stop])

Compare Our Models¶

Naive Bayes Results:¶

Despite its reputation as a good choice for text mining, this model had the poorest performance with just 78% accuracy! However, it had a great precision score (99%) which indicated that it had a great ability of detecting real news. For someone who wants to detect real news for more credibility , this is the right choice

RNN Results:¶

  • It was quite disappointing to witness that our model did not have the best performance on the test set ( only 90% accuracy ) considering that it had 98% accuracy on the training set. This high variance is probably due to the lack of data ( only 6000 rows ). Such problems can be solved with data augmentation (which was not possible) or regularization which improved our performance slightly from 88% to almost 90%.

In [ ]:
fpr_lr, tpr_lr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, lr_pred)
roc_auc_lr = auc(fpr_lr, tpr_lr)
fpr_nb, tpr_nb, _ = roc_curve(y_test, nb_pred)
roc_auc_nb = auc(fpr_nb, tpr_nb)
fpr_rnn, tpr_rnn, _ = roc_curve(y_test, rnn_pred)
roc_auc_rnn = auc(fpr_rnn, tpr_rnn)
fpr_pac, tpr_pac, _ = roc_curve(y_test, pac_pred)
roc_auc_pac = auc(fpr_pac, tpr_pac)
fpr_svc, tpr_svc, _ = roc_curve(y_test, svc_pred)
roc_auc_svc = auc(fpr_svc, tpr_svc)


plt.figure(figsize=(16, 9))
plt.xlim([-0.01, 1.00])
plt.ylim([-0.01, 1.01])
plt.plot(fpr_lr, tpr_lr, lw=3, label='LogRegr ROC curve (area = {:0.2f})'.format(roc_auc_lr))
plt.plot(fpr_svc, tpr_svc, lw=3, label='SVM ROC curve (area = {:0.2f})'.format(roc_auc_svc))
plt.plot(fpr_rnn, tpr_rnn, lw=3, label='RNN ROC curve (area = {:0.2f})'.format(roc_auc_rnn))
plt.plot(fpr_pac, tpr_pac, lw=3, label='PassAgg ROC curve (area = {:0.2f})'.format(roc_auc_pac))
plt.plot(fpr_nb, tpr_nb, lw=3, label='Naive Bayes ROC curve (area = {:0.2f})'.format(roc_auc_nb))
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate', fontsize=16)
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate', fontsize=16)
plt.title('ROC curve', fontsize=16)
plt.legend(loc='lower right', fontsize=13)
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='navy', lw=3, linestyle='--')
plt.axes().set_aspect('equal')
plt.show()

AUC indicated that the best algorithms were SVM and Passive Aggressive Classifier. However, there is a small difference in their performance:

  • If one is looking for detecting real news in order to gain more credibility, the better choice would be SVM .
  • However, if their goal is to detect and eliminate fake news, the wise decision would be to choose Passive Aggressive Classifier.
